THIS SECTION OF THE SPREADSHEET AUTOMATICALLY CHECKS THE ESTIMATES FOR POSSIBLE ERRORS/INCONSISTENCIES
Highlighted cells indicate possible error in the corresponding estimate table

column1: For each species group and each management strategy, please provide your estimates of the following in the table below:
1. Realistically, what is your best guess for the probability of persistence of the species group under the given management strategy?
2. Realistically, what do you think is the lowest plausible (most pessimistic) probability of persistence of the species group under the given strategy?
3. Realistically, what do you think is the highest plausible (most optimistic) probability of persistence of the species group under the given management strategy?
4. How confident are you that your interval, from lowest to highest, includes the true probability of persistence? (Please enter a number between 50% and 100%)
YOU DO NOT HAVE TO GIVE AN ESTIMATE FOR EVERY SPECIES GROUP AND/OR STRATEGY

If you do not feel confident making an estimate, please put an 'X' in the cell. 
If you think the species will not be affected by the management strategy, use 'B' to indicate that the effect is the same as the baseline scenario
column120: CHECK IF THE PERFORMANCE OF THE STRATEGY IS HIGHER THAN THE BASELINE
column187: CHECK IF THE BENEFIT (=STRATEGY-BASELINE) UNDER THE COMBINED STRATEGY IS HIGHER THAN THE BENEFIT UNDER THE INDIVIDUAL STRATEGY

column120: Negative values = Estimate for baseline is higher than for strategy;

column117: I should mention that we are investigating translocation of Furbish's Lousewort.   I don't have much faith that it will work because of the habitat issue - climate change effects on the flows of the Upper Saint John River. Scoring for pollution reflects concerns re mercury and lead in Bald Eagle - not found to be major concern here yet.
column118: much uncertainty in efficacy of strategies makes it hard to estimate improvement with combinations

column117: I am having a hard time separating the wetland habitat management  from the policy strategy.  I have favoured the policy because I believe it does more to protect large wetlands. I don't see pollution as a large problem.  I think wetlands are one system where we might be able to consider some mitigation around climate change, but I don't know what that would look like.

Re public land management, we may feel we are making  a difference for Monarch - I am not sure we can make a real difference at our scale and latitude.  Not sure the proposals under climate change will work. There may be some habitat for these species in wetlands (meadows).
